IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
Maryland State Annapolis Barrack
The incident was captured on my body-worn camera 
Defendant: Payton Dayle Minor   
Date of Birth: 05/01/1997
Date of Arrest: 02/16/2023
Time of Arrest: 2210
Maryland Driver’s License: M-560-676-135-334 
DUI# J-23-028

Training and Certification:
 *I am trained by the Maryland State Police and the National Highway Transportation Safety Administration to administer Standardized Field Sobriety Tests.
 *I am a certified Preliminary Breath Test operator.
 *I have completed Advanced Roadside Impaired Driving Enforcement (ARIDE) training.
 
 
 VEHICLE IN MOTION (PHASE 1)
 
 On 02/16/2023 at approximately 2154 hours, I TFC. J. Hill (6278) was dispatched to the area of Tidewater Colony Drive at Bestgate Rd, Annapolis, Maryland 21401 to assist Sgt. Bigham (#4826) with a traffic stop (see Sgt Bigham’s supplement for moving violations observed.) As I arrived on the scene, I turned on my rear emergency equipment and parked my patrol vehicle behind Sgt. Bigham’s patrol vehicle.   
 
 
 PERSONAL CONTACT (PHASE 2)
 
 I made contact with Sgt. Bigham and he advised me the driver of his traffic stop may be under the influence of alcohol. I made contact with the operator who was identified by her Maryland driver’s license as Payton Dayle Minor (DOB: 05/01/1997 2/F) via the driver’s side front window. Upon making contact, I immediately smelled the very strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from the interior of the vehicle.
 
 I requested Minor exit her vehicle, to which she complied. I asked Minor where she was coming from and she advised downtown Annapolis. I asked Minor how much alcohol she had to drink and she stated “I don’t know 1 drink or 2.” I asked Minor if she had 1 or 2 drinks, and she said “yeah.” As I spoke with Minor, I intentionally observed Minor’s speech to be slurred and her eyes to be bloodshot and glassy. As Minor spoke, I could still smell the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from her breath and person. I informed Minor that I would be performing field sobriety tests on her, which she agreed to submit. 
 
 PRE-ARREST SCREENING (PHASE 3)
 
The evaluation was performed in front of Minor’s vehicle. The surface was dry, level, and free from any obvious debris. The weather was clear and approximately 55 degrees. The lighting conditions consisted of the street lamps and my flashlight. All patrol vehicle's  forward facing emergency lights were deactivated during all three tests. Minor did not display any visible injuries. 
 
 I asked Minor the following questions:
 Medication - NO.  
 Contacts – No. 

The first test given was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus test. The tip of my pen was used as the test’s stimulus and held approximately 12 inches from Minor’s eyes. Minor was instructed to look straight ahead, keeping her head still while following and focusing on the tip of the stimulus with her eyes until told to stop. Minor’s pupils were equal in size and showed equal tracking. Minor was asked if she understood the directions and she stated “yes.” Minor was positioned in a manner to ensure the headlights of passing traffic would not interfere with the test results.
 
 HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS (6/6 clues observed)
 
1. Lack of Smooth Pursuit – Present in both eyes.
2. Distinct and sustained Nystagmus at Maximum Deviation - Present in both eyes.
3. Onset of Nystagmus Prior to 45 Degrees - Present in both eyes.

Other observations:
1. Minor had difficulty following my pen with just her eyes (moved her head).
2. Minor was swaying from side to side during the test.  
 
 
 
WALK AND TURN (4/8 clues observed)
 
 Prior to Minor performing the test, I properly explained and demonstrated how the test should be conducted. Minor was instructed to place her right foot directly in front of her left foot and touch heel to toe. Minor was instructed to place her hands flat at her side and to remain in the position until told to begin. Minor was advised to take nine (9) steps in a straight-line touching heel to toe on every step. Minor was told to keep her hands flat at her side, keeping her eyes focused on her feet, and count every step aloud. Minor was demonstrated and explained to keep her lead foot on the line and to take a series of small steps around with her rear foot to turn completely around. Minor was again explained and demonstrated the second series of nine (9) steps were to be performed identical to the first series. After explaining and demonstrating the test, I asked Minor if she completely understood the instructions and she stated “yes.” 
 
 Instructional Stage: 
 1. Lost balance – Feet broke apart on one (1) occasion.
 
 Walking Stage (First 9 Steps)
 1. Missed heel to toe by more than an inch on steps 2 through 9. 

 Turn:
 1. Turned around by turning on both feet at the same time.
 
 Walking Stage (Second 9 Steps)
1. Missed heel to toe by more than an inch on steps 1 through 6, 8, and 9.
2. Stepped off the line by more than the width of a foot on step 8.
 
 
 ONE LEG STAND (3/4 clues observed)
 
 Prior to Minor performing the test, I properly explained and demonstrated how the test should be conducted. Minor was instructed to stand with her heels together and hands down by her side while the instructions were given during the test. Minor was instructed not to begin the test until she was told to start and after the test had been demonstrated. When instructed to start, she was to raise the foot of her choice off the ground approximately 6 inches. While her leg was raised she was to keep her leg straight, watch her raised foot, and count out loud by thousands (one thousand - one, one thousand - two) and continue the test until told to stop. Minor was asked if she understood the test and the instructions to which she stated “yes.” 
 
 Instructional Stage:
 1. Nothing to report. 
 
 Balance and Count Stage:
 
 Seconds 0-10
1. Raised arms by more than six inches away from her body.
2. Placed foot down on three (3) occasions. 
3. Swayed body from side to side by more than three inches. 
 
 Seconds 11-20
1. Raised arms by more than six inches away from her body.
2. Placed foot on the ground on one (1) occasion.
 
 Seconds 21-30 
1. Placed foot on the ground on one (1) occasion.
 
 ARREST:
 
 Based on the following:                                    
*Sgt. Bigham’s observations of Minor’s driving. 
*Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from the interior of the vehicle. 
 *Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from her breath and person.
 *Slurred Speech.
 *Her glassy and bloodshot eyes.
*Admission to consuming 1 or 2 alcoholic beverages.  
 * My observed signs of impairment as she performed Standardized Field Sobriety Test.
 
 
 Given the aforementioned observation, I believed Minor could not operate a motor vehicle safely and was placed under arrest at approximately 2210 hours on 02/16/202 for driving under the influence of alcohol. Minor was transported in the front passenger seat of my patrol vehicle to the Maryland State Police Annapolis Barrack for processing. While at the barrack, I played the English audio version of the DR -15 Advice of Rights to her in its entirety. At the conclusion of the form, Minor agreed to submit to the intoximeter test and signed the DR-15 indicating the same 2239 hours).

20-MINUTE OBSERVATION PERIOD
CPL. Engleman #5835 and I conducted the 20-minute observation period with Minor. A preliminary search of Minor was conducted at the barrack and it revealed that she did not have anything in her mouth at 2230 hours. CPL. Engleman #5835 and I observed Minor from the time the preliminary search was conducted until the time she submitted to the test and she did not put anything in her mouth. The test was conducted by CPL. Engleman #5835 of the Maryland State Police on a certified instrument. Minor had a result of 0.15 grams of alcohol per 210 liters of breath at 2253 hours.
 
 
 INTOXIMETER RESULT:
 *** MINOR’S INTOXIMETER RESULTS: 0.15***
 
 
 Minor was given all copies of pertinent paperwork and released to a sober driver.
 Minor was polite and cooperative during the encounter. 
 Case closed by arrest.
 All events occurred in Anne Arundel County, Maryland.

On 2/16/2023 at approximately 2152 hours, I Sgt. J. Bigham #4826, was operating unmarked patrol vehicle J25 in the area of N/B Rowe Blvd prior to Rt. 50. I observed a gray Lexus passenger vehicle bearing Maryland registration 9FF7371 traveling in lane #2. I observed the vehicle with the left blinker on drive from lane #2 onto the right shoulder with both passenger side tires crossing over the solid right shoulder line. The vehicle then drove back into lane #2. The vehicle with the left blinker still activated then drove from lane #2 slightly into the right E/B Rt. 50 entrance ramp lane with both passenger side tires crossing over. The vehicle came back into lane #2 and then changed from lane #2 into lane #1. The vehicle then drove from lane #1 into lane #2 with both passenger side tires crossing over into lane #2 before coming back into lane #1.

Based my observations I activated my emergency equipment to initiate a traffic stop on the vehicle. The vehicle made a left turn onto Tidewater Colony Drive and came to a stop on the right side of the roadway. Before contacting the driver, I requested TFC J. Hill respond to my location. Upon contact with the driver I immediately detected a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage coming from the driver. Additionally, I observed the driver had red and glassy eyes. The driver was identified by her Maryland Driver’s License as Payton Dayle Minor, W/F, DOB 5/1/1997. The driver advised she was coming from “downtown Annapolis” and had “1 beer.” A very short time later TFC J. Hill arrived and began field sobriety testing on the driver.

All the above events occurred in Anne Arundel County, Maryland.
